# Runtime `tsdown build()` must be isolated from the package build config

Some packages call tsdown's programmatic `build()` at **runtime** (not as their
own build step) — e.g. `@prisma/app-node` and `@prisma/app-nextjs` bundle the
user's server inside `assemble()` during `prisma-app deploy`.

tsdown's `build()` **auto-discovers a `tsdown.config.ts`** from the working
directory. Every publishable package now has one (it enables tsdown's `exports`
management so the manifest tracks the built entries). If a runtime `build()`
picks that config up, tsdown **rewrites the package's own `package.json`
`exports`** to point at the throwaway bundle output — after which every later
resolution of that package fails (`Cannot find module` under bun; `Invalid
"exports" main target "/tmp/…"` under node).

## Rule

Any runtime `build(...)` call MUST pass `config: false`:

```ts
await build({
  entry: [serviceModule],
  outDir: bundleDir,
  // …
  config: false, // do NOT auto-load this package's tsdown.config.ts
});
```

A runtime bundle is self-contained: it supplies its options inline and must never
read — or mutate — a package manifest.

## Why this is easy to miss

It only bites once a package has both a `tsdown.config.ts` **and** a runtime
`build()` call, and the symptom is a corrupted `package.json` that surfaces as a
*resolution* failure in an unrelated test — see
[`workspace-package-not-found`](./workspace-package-not-found.mdc).
